      "id":"football/2013/oct/22/alex-ferguson-my-autobiography-launch",
      "sectionId":"football",
      "sectionName":"Football",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-22T18:04:15Z",
      "webTitle":"Alex Ferguson's latest autobiography reveals all (and why he was right)",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/oct/22/alex-ferguson-my-autobiography-launch",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/football/2013/oct/22/alex-ferguson-my-autobiography-launch",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"3",
        "trailText":"David Beckham, Rio Ferdinand, Wayne Rooney: Fergie spills the beans and gives a lesson in how to be a terrible ex-manager",
        "headline":"Alex Ferguson's latest autobiography reveals all (and why he was right)",
        "body":"<p>Sir Alex Ferguson may have retired from football management, but like a deposed postwar prime minister his memoirs live on. Part news story, part superheated publishing beano and without doubt the most swaggeringly A-list football book of the year, decade and – it seems safe to say – entire spectrum of past and future time, Sir Alex Ferguson's autobiography is finally upon us.</p><p>Unveiled at a launch-cum-press-event on Pall Mall, the book itself was available under strict pre-launch embargo from the publishers Hodder &amp; Stoughton at 10 o'clock sharp on Tuesday morning.</p><p>And so it arrived in convoy, glossily packaged, and coming in at a muscular 402 large-type pages, all fronted up by a wonderfully stark full-face Fergie portrait: imperious, gently amused and posed against a sheer white background like some benevolent creator.</p><p>To give My Autobiography its due it is hard to imagine, in outline, a more potent footballing memoir. Ferguson's retirement last May brought to an end the greatest career in English football's recent years of plenty.</p><p>Ferguson not only straddled but helped to define the transformation of an industry, his 27 years at Manchester United entirely bound up in this violently hot-housed blooming from marginalised popular sport to thrummingly unavoidable celebrity entertainment vehicle.</p><p>Throughout, Ferguson was the most important man in the most important job in the nation's most vibrantly territorial popular spectacle. More than this he was abrasive, confrontational and charismatic, an imperial lord of the Premier League touchline. Ferguson doesn't just know where the bodies are. He buried most of them himself. In short, this was always likely to be worth a squizz.</p><p>The first thing to say about My Autobiography is that it isn't really an autobiography. It is instead a continuation of the accumulated Ferguson life story, as told in the 16 (at a quick count) biographies and autobiographies already out there.</p><p>In effect this is the semi-detached second volume of Managing My Life, published in 1999 and written with the great Hugh McIlvanney. As such My Autobiography kicks off with a 17-page section called \"Glasgow roots\" before leaping to 2001 and Ferguson's decision to cancel his impending retirement and settle down instead to 12 years of fevered and macro-cosmically fraught football management.</p><p>The first real heavy hits are landed in the early David Beckham chapter. This is misleadingly polite to start with – \"I hold no rancour towards David. I like him\" – before settling down into a beautifully paced hatchet job by stealth: not so much the hairdryer as a gently malevolent towelling down.</p><p>\"David is the only player I ever managed who chose to be famous,\" Ferguson notes, before giving chapter and verse on his many other failings right down to Beckham's refusal to remove his beanie hat during a formal team meal in a restaurant in order to hide (for media-related reasons) his newly shaved head. Ferguson sticks up for Rio Ferdinand: the missed drugs test in 2003 was the fault of the testers. There is a love letter of a chapter on Cristiano Ronaldo, while Roy Keane is elegantly filleted, and described here, in effect, as a vaguely disturbed individual.</p><p>José Mourinho is treated with respect, albeit mentions of Roman Abramovich's vast spending on his behalf at Chelsea are never far away.</p><p>Best of all, there is a good, fresh chapter about his gathering sense of disappointment with Wayne Rooney, which starts with Ferguson signing Rooney from a weeping Everton chairman, Bill Kenwright (\"they're stealing our boy, they're stealing our boy\"). Elsewhere Ferguson rambles across politics, taking in his advice to Tony Blair in 1997 (\"keep your government in one room and lock the door and you'll have no problems … Tony was receptive to that message\") and recounting the story of Blair asking his advice on whether to sack Gordon Brown or not. The potentially disastrous wrangle over the racehorse Rock of Gibraltar gets short shrift, as do the media (basically he hates the media). And in many ways this is the tone. The big subjects are broached. Ferguson raises his double-barrel. Boom. Off they go. My Autobiography doesn't have a subtitle, but \"Why I was right all along …\" might have been a good choice.</p><p>This is undoubtedly an excellent football book, as it could hardly fail to be given the richness of its source material, while Paul Hayward, Ferguson's ghost, captures his voice perfectly throughout.</p><p>For all that there is nothing really startling here. How could there be, really, in a resumé of a life lived almost entirely beneath the compound eye of football's mass media. In the end My Autobiography is remarkable in two respects. It is undoubtedly the most voraciously hyped footballing memoir of all time, a publishing event of such visceral force it came as something of a surprise to receive the hardback copy in a simple bubble-wrap envelope as opposed to say, a lead-lined coffin.</p><p>This has not happened before and it will probably not happen again. It is of its time, a product of 23 years of intensely enacted pre-publicity.</p><p>Second, while Ferguson may be the greatest British manager of all time, he continues to give a fascinating lesson in how to be an absolutely terrible ex-manager. Looming in the stands, name-checked in every press conference and now available in headline-grabbing book form, he is for his successor, David Moyes, the managerial equivalent of the father-in-law from hell, continually asserting, as here, his continued and undiluted power to fascinate and control.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420672453|2013-10-23T17:15:08Z|e07b5e4c08cc02bf22d89c1f56753259daf16485 -->",
